        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1884740436" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13547721823930276002"><b>“Prince&apos;s music calmed me as much as masturbation or a cheeseburger.”</b> <br/>Lionel Essrog, protagonist in Lethem&apos;s <i>Motherless Brooklyn</i><br/><br/><img src='https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1484801438ra/21754904.gif' width='325' height='234' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/><br/>Lethem&apos;s 1999 literary detective novel set in Brooklyn was a fun read, much more layered and satisfying than the hard-boiled detective novels. The protagonist Lionel Essrog grew up an orphan and was nicknamed &quot;The Human Freakshow&quot; due to his Tourette syndrome. In lesser hands, these verbal tics could have turned gimmicky, but here Lethem fully develops Essrog and makes </span>
  <span id="freeText13547721823930276002" style="display:none"><b>“Prince's music calmed me as much as masturbation or a cheeseburger.”</b> <br>Lionel Essrog, protagonist in Lethem's <i>Motherless Brooklyn</i><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1484801438ra/21754904.gif" width="325" height="234" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><br>Lethem's 1999 literary detective novel set in Brooklyn was a fun read, much more layered and satisfying than the hard-boiled detective novels. The protagonist Lionel Essrog grew up an orphan and was nicknamed "The Human Freakshow" due to his Tourette syndrome. In lesser hands, these verbal tics could have turned gimmicky, but here Lethem fully develops Essrog and makes the reader care about him.<br><br>Essrog is working for Frank Minna, who has some mob connections and owns a "seedy," "makeshift" detective agency (a front for two-bit organized crime), when Minna is murdered by stabbing. Essrog's suspenseful journey investigating and solving the crime is always intelligent and often risible.<br></span>
  <a data-text-id="13547721823930276002" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
